1. Introduction

 This documentation is about the XMMS2 player proxy. This proxy is actually a
script (which can be started automatically by the XMMS2 daemon).

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

2. Requirements

  •  Remuco server >= 0.7.1

  •  XMMS2 Python bindings >= 0.2DrJekyll

  •  Python DBUS bindings (python-dbus)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

3. Installation

3.1. System

 For system wide installation run (as root):

 $ make install

 This installs the player proxy into /usr/bin. To let XMMS2 start the proxy
automatically, each user has to create a symbolic to /usr/bin/remuco-xmms2 from
the XMMS2 startup script directory:

 $ ln -s /usr/bin/remuco-xmms2 ~/.config/xmms2/startup.d

Note You can adjust the install destination by setting the environment variable
     PREFIX (/usr is used as default).

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

3.2. User

 For user specific installation, run:

 $ make install-user

 This installs the player proxy into ~/.config/xmms2/startup.d

 On the next start of XMMS2, the proxy gets started automatically.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

4. Usage

 If you've installed the XMMS2 player proxy into the XMMS2 startup script
directory (as described above), then it gets started automatically by XMMS2.
The XMMS2 player proxy automatically starts the Remuco server. So actually you
do not have to do anything.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

5. Troubleshooting

 To track down errors, please try the steps below. If this does not solve your
problem, come to the help forum.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

5.1. General

 If something fails, it is a good idea to set Remuco into debug mode. You can
toggle the debug mode for the server and all player proxies with the tool
remuco using option --debug. Running

 $ remuco

 tells you if debug mode is on or off. Running

 $ remuco --debug

 switches between enabled and disabled debug mode.

 The server log can be found in ~/.cache/remuco/Server.log. Logging of basic
player proxies (e.g. Amarok, Banshee, MPD, Totem) goes to ~/.cache/remuco/
PLAYER.log where PLAYER means the basic player proxy's player name. Log sinks
of full player proxies (e.g. Rhythmbox, XMMS2) are proxy specific.

 Inspect the relevant log files to detect what is wrong.

Note Don't forget to disable debug mode once you do not need it anymore -
     otherwise you might get quite big log files when running Remuco for
     several hours.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

5.2. XMMS2

 To debug the XMMS2 player proxy, remove it from the XMMS2 startup script
directory and start it manually (when XMMS2 is running) to see its logging:

 $ xmms2 quit

 $ mv ~/.config/xmms2/startup.d/remuco-xmms2 ~/

 $ xmms2-launcher

 $ ~/remuco-xmms2

The log output hopefully indicates the problem.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

